Peel and grate the @garlic clove{4} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #medium saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once the oil is hot, add half the garlic and cook for ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in the @water{220%ml} and @chicken stock paste{10%g} and bring to the boil.

When boiling, remove from the heat, stir in the @couscous{110%g} and pop a #lid{} on the pan.

Leave to the side for ~{8-10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #large frying pan{} on
medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced chicken thigh{260%g} and @baby plum tomatoes{125%g}. Season
with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fry until the chicken is golden brown on the outside, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Stir the remaining garlic and @balsamic glaze{12%ml} into the pan until combined.

Squish the tomatoes until they burst, then add the remaining @chicken stock paste{10%g},
@sugar{1/2%tsp} and @water{75%ml}.

Bring the sauce to a simmer and reduce until slightly thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once thickened, remove from the heat and vigorously stir in the cold
@butter{10%g}.

Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Stir the @fresh pesto{50%g} through the couscous and fluff up with a #fork{}.

Share the pesto couscous between your bowls, then top with the chicken and smashed
tomato sauce.

Crumble the @Greek style salad cheese{50%g} over the top to finish.

Enjoy!